    <title>Combined summary - Proposal: remove "getwork" RPC from bitcoind</title>
    <updated>2023-06-07T16:22:37.961993+00:00</updated>
    <link href="https://lists.linuxfoundation.org/pipermail/bitcoin-dev/2013-August/003185.html" rel="alternate"/>
    <summary>The Bitcoin development community is currently discussing the proposal to remove the "getwork" RPC from Bitcoind, which was once widely used but has now become unnecessary and problematic. On mainnet, almost everyone now uses a pool and not "getwork" directly to Bitcoind. Those who solo mine use a pool server to communicate with Bitcoind via "getblocktemplate" or other means. Tests have shown that attempting to solo mine on mainnet via "getwork" leads to delays and problems. Although getwork may continue to work on testnet, there are open source pool servers available for testnet, which eliminates the need to support getwork.Jeff Garzik, Senior Software Engineer and open source evangelist at BitPay, has proposed to remove "getwork" and gauge responses to ensure they are not breaking anything unnecessarily. However, some members of the community believe that removing "getwork" could lead Bitcoin towards a monopoly/cartel model by favoring only pool operators and private mining interests, denying novice miners the ability to mine at a small scale, even if it is currently inefficient. In an email exchange from 2013, a user named Frank F strongly objected to the removal of the getwork API in Bitcoin mining, claiming that it was the only mechanism allowing anyone to say that Bitcoin is peer-to-peer (P2P) in the truest sense. Pieter Wuille responded by explaining that the getwork API had been replaced with a more decentralization-friendly successor API called getblocktemplate, which allows callers to see what transactions the daemon is trying to put into a block and modify them. Wuille clarified that the suggestion was not to remove functionality but rather to remove an obsolete API.Suggestions were made for alternative methods of mining that could be used instead of desktop CPUs, such as USB sticks capable of reaching 500MH/s. Some users also suggested packaging up modern mining tools that support CPU/GPU/FPGA/ASIC mining against a current Bitcoind to salvage a non-functioning network in the event of a massive drop in hash rate or a great depression in network hash rate. Nevertheless, the aim is to first clean up the code enough so that it can be understood and eventually taken over to a real Windows project/solution where it can be made into an executable that is palatable for the masses.In general, the discussions revolve around the practical implications of the proposed changes to Bitcoin mining and how they could affect the functionality of testnet-in-a-box. Suggestions were made for alternative methods of mining that could be used instead of desktop CPUs, such as USB sticks capable of reaching 500MH/s. Some users also suggested packaging up modern mining tools that support CPU/GPU/FPGA/ASIC mining against a current bitcoind to salvage a non-functioning network in the event of a massive drop in hash rate or a great depression in network hash rate.Gregory Maxwell suggests packaging up a modern mining tool that supports CPU/GPU/FPGA/ASIC mining against a current bitcoind to ensure that a full network node is provided, while Matt agrees that there is no reason to leave broken things that aren't necessary. In an email exchange from August 2013, Warren suggested the idea of shipping a miner that automatically reads the Bitcoin.conf file to find RPC authentication information, which would be faster and more efficient than the unoptimized miner and simplify the bitcoind code.The hashrate in the Bitcoin network is growing at such a rapid pace that soon, all desktop CPUs combined won't be able to make a significant impact on it. However, one can purchase a USB stick capable of reaching 500MH/s for just $20, which manufacturers could potentially ship with a built-in miner program. The discussion also includes removing the internal miner and getwork from Litecoin 0.8.x, adding GBT support to aid in the goal of removing the internal miner and getwork completely, and suggestions for proper mining tools to ensure a full network node is provided.Overall, it seems that removing "getwork" would be a logical step forward as it is no longer widely used and has proven to be problematic in certain situations. The proposal has received mixed reactions, with some concerned that it would lock out individual novice miners while favoring only pool operators and private mining interests. However, others have pointed out that getblocktemplate does everything getwork did and more, making it just the removal of an obsolete API. In addition, there are discussions about the annoyance of testing and how regtest mode can be useful, and the potential removal of certain accounting features in Freicoin.</summary>
